The exchange rate data has a mean of 68.45. The kurtosis value is less than 3.0, implying a platykurtic nature. Platykurtosis measures the extremity of the data of a probability distribution. A normal bell-shaped distribution is mesokurtic. A distribution that has less extreme values than the normal distribution is considered platykurtic. Thus the platykurtic distribution has lighter tails than a normal distribution with few values at the extreme ends of the curve. A leptokurtic distribution has more extreme data than the normal curve.

Inference from ACF and PACF¶

The ACF is decaying exponentially and the PACF exhibits a damped sinosoidal pattern. From the PACF of the first lag is significant in the autoregregressive process. From the ACF plot, the lags fall insignificant beyond 115 lags. The autocorrelations are significant for a large number of lags (about 115) because the autocorrelation of lags 2 and above are perhaps, merely a propagation of the autocorrelation at lag 1. This again is confirmed by the PACF plot.

Tests for Stationarity¶

It seems that the series exhibits both AR(p) and MA(q) terms. But to be certain one has to conduct tests for stationarity on the data using statistical tests such as the Augmented Dickey Fuller test.

Types of stationarity¶

  • Strict Stationary: Satisfies the mathematical conditions for strict stationarity.

  • Trend Stationary: Series that has no unit root but exhibits a trend. Once the trend is removed, the resulting series will be strict stationary. The KPSS test classifies a series as stationary on the absence of unit root. This means that the series can be strict stationary or trend stationary.

  • Difference Stationary: A time series that can be made strict stationary by differencing falls under difference stationary. ADF test is also known as a difference stationarity test.

Case 1: Both tests conclude that the series is not stationary -> series is not stationary

Case 2: Both tests conclude that the series is stationary -> series is stationary

Case 3: KPSS = stationary and ADF = not stationary -> trend stationary, remove the trend to make series strict stationary

Case 4: KPSS = not stationary and ADF = stationary -> difference stationary, use differencing to make series stationary

Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF) Test on original data¶

The hypotheses at 5 percent significance level are:

$H_0$: The time series is not stationary.
$H_1$: The time series is stationary.

Our objective is to reject the null hypothesis when the p-value is less that 0.05 and ensure stationarity of the time series data

In [185]:
#define function for ADF test
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def adf_test(timeseries):
    #Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
    print ('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test: \n')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
       dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print (dfoutput)

#apply adf test on the series
adf_test(df_daily.inrVal)

Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:

Test Statistic                   -0.427478
p-value                           0.905409
#Lags Used                        0.000000
Number of Observations Used    1642.000000
Critical Value (1%)              -3.434339
Critical Value (5%)              -2.863302
Critical Value (10%)             -2.567708
dtype: float64

Since p-value is greater that 0.05, we cannot reject the null hypothesis. The exchange rate time series is in fact non-stationary.

This calls for a transformation that would make the data stationary. One could calculate the differences or obtain the logarithmic returns of the exchange rate data. The reason one uses returns rather than actual exchange rate values is that returns have more suitable statistical properties than rates (CAMPBELL). Logarithmic returns (continuously compounded returns) are used frequently, which we adopt here.

The log returns are defined as follows.

$$ r_t = \ln\left(\frac{y_t}{y_{t-1}}\right) $$

Here, $y_t$ is the exchange rate on day $t$ and $y_{t-1}$ is its first lag. Note that the number of observations in the series used for analysis drops again by one to 1641.

Shapiro-Wilk Test of Normality¶

The Shapiro–Wilk test checks whether the sample came from a normally distributed population. The null hypothesis that is that the data is normally distributed, which is rejected with a p-value less than 0.05.

In [83]:
shapiro_test = stats.shapiro(df_daily.returns)
shapiro_test
Out[83]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.8919786214828491, pvalue=1.890033579522588e-32)

The results show that $W = 0.892 $ with p <0.05. Hence reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the returns are not normally distributed. (CANAN CORLU 2013)

Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin (KPSS) Test¶

The KPSS test is also used to test for stationarity of time-series data. The null hypothesis for the KPSS test and the ADF test are opposites.

The hypotheses at 5 percent significance level are:

$H_0$: The time series is trend stationary.
$H_1$: The time series a unit root (series is not stationary).

In [93]:
# KPSS on exchange rate value
def kpss_test(series, **kw):
    statistic, p_value, n_lags, critical_values = kpss(series, **kw)
    # Format Output
    print(f'KPSS Statistic: {statistic}')
    print(f'p-value: {p_value}')
    print(f'num lags: {n_lags}')
    print('Critial Values:')
    for key, value in critical_values.items():
        print(f'   {key} : {value}')
    print(f'Result: The series is {"not " if p_value < 0.05 else ""}stationary')

kpss_test(df_daily.inrVal)

Ljung-Box Test¶

$H_0$: The residuals are uncorrelated. $H_1$: The residuals are correlated.

In both the ARMA(10,6) and the auto-arima indicated ARIMA(1,0,1) models, the p value > 0.05. Hence accept the null that residuals are uncorrelated.

The fact that we cannot use this model to forecast effectively means that the model residuals are closer to being white noise. However, even in this case there could be volatility clustering, ie., periods of high volatility followed by periods of high volatility and vice versa.

Therefore, we use ARCH, GARCH models.
